"Cc" and "bcc" are abbreviations used in email communication to indicate the recipients of a message.

"Cc" stands for "carbon copy" and is used to indicate that a message is being sent to multiple recipients. When someone is "cc'd" on an email, they receive a copy of the message and can see all the other recipients in the "To" and "Bcc" fields. "Cc" is also used as a shorthand for "cc:ing" someone, meaning that you are sending a copy of the message to the person.

"Bcc" stands for "blind carbon copy" and is used to send a copy of the message to multiple recipients without revealing all the email addresses to each other. When someone is "bcc'd" on an email, they receive a copy of the message, but only the email addresses in the "To" field are visible to them. "Bcc" is also used as a shorthand for "bcc:ing" someone, meaning that you are sending a blind carbon copy of the message to the person.

In both cases, the recipients can reply to the message and their messages will go to all the other recipients, whether they are in the "To," "Cc," or "Bcc" fields. It's important to use these fields correctly to avoid unintentionally sending a message to an unintended recipient or leaving someone out of the loop.
